<section id="socioeconomic">
  <h1>Socioeconomic Microsimulations</h1>

  <p>Understanding how households and individuals experience policy choices and potential shocks is key to ensuring that benefits are inclusive and no one is left behind. Microsimulations offer insights for policies to eradicate poverty, reduce inequality, enhance food security and broaden access to energy, among others. The technique has been applied to policies related to taxes or subsidies, cash or in-kind transfers, and expanded access to modern energy, among other examples.</p>

  <div class="projects">
    <div class="t-col" style="background-image: url(/images/photos/kids-walking.jpg)">
      <div class="fuzz"></div>
      <h3>Growth and Social Inclusion</h3>

      <div class="t-gutter">
        <a onclick="_show_aside(this);">About</a>
        <a href="/tada?project=growth-social-inclusion">Visualisation</a>
      </div>

      <aside>
        <div class="content">
          <p>This analysis combines two modelling tools, an economy-wide model and microsimulation.
            <ul>
              <li>The economy-wide model analyses the effects of rapid growth and different financing options in implementing education, health and sanitation policies. Model simulations suggest that economic growth greatly facilitates the achievement of education, health and sanitation goals. The analysis also suggests, however, that in the absence of fast economic growth, the financial burden of implementing these policies increases dramatically.</li>
              <li>The microsimulation exercise analyses the impact of macroeconomic shocks on household income, notably labour income. This generates a mapping of the effects of implementing health, education and sanitation policies on poverty and income distribution for a number of key household groups.</li>
            </ul>
          </p>
        </div>
      </aside>
    </div>

    <div class="t-col" style="background-image: url(/images/photos/electricity-poles.jpg)">
      <div class="fuzz"></div>
      <h3>Estimating Electricity Consumption Using HH Surveys</h3>

      <div class="t-gutter">
        <a onclick="_show_aside(this);">About</a>
      </div>

      <aside>
        <div class="content">
          <p>Estimating the demand for electricity is a critical step in the design of a medium- to long-term energy plan. Frequently, estimates are based on time series data with few observation points or on data from other countries or regions. Even if data exist over a number of years and for detailed energy services, estimates often cannot easily take into account changes in policies.</p>
          <p>Microsimulation models shed light on how the demand for energy can change under “what-if” scenarios. Based on household surveys or administrative data, microsimulation can estimate energy demand for the entire distribution of households or beneficiaries, and thereby offer some evidence of how, for example, redistributive policies can affect the overall demand for energy.</p>

          <p>Supplementary material is available <a href="https://github.com/un-modelling/Electricity_Consumption_Surveys">here</a>.</p>
        </div>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="energy-systems">
  <h1>Energy Systems Models</h1>

  <p>Energy systems models can be used for energy policy analysis or to conduct medium- and long-term energy planning. They can help assess the interplay between the technical and economic characteristics of energy technologies, and explore how technology choice impacts energy security, access and affordability, as well as the environment.</p>

